Neobule‚ love-sici< for her Hebrus complains that she cannot give free rein to her love or wash away its pain in deep draughts ot wine. All interest in her spinning is taken from her by the thought of the beauty of her lover, who excels as swimmer, horseman, boner, muner, and hunter. '

There has been some discussion among critics as to the nature of this ode, but it is best regarded as a monologue. lt is the only experi- ment in pure lonic measure that Horace has left υς, and is an imitation of verses by Alcaeus, of which the opening lineis preserved (Frg. 59) ἔμε δείλαν, ἔμε πασᾶν κακοτατῶν πεδέχοισαν.
